  <entry>
    <id>2</id>
    <title>Combined summary - PQC: Lattice-based signatures</title>
    <updated>2026-06-02T05:34:16.298735+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/b3988d19-b1b8-49ed-82c5-1447f37bf473n@googlegroups.com/T/#mc3c5bbaef94d6f30763350488814d239a146652f" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-05-19 19:33:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The recent discussions on the Bitcoin Development Mailing List have revolved around the potential adoption of post-quantum cryptographic (PQC) signatures, particularly focusing on hash-based and lattice-based approaches. A key point raised in these discussions concerns the conservative nature of hash-based signatures, which are valued for their simplicity, efficiency, and forward compatibility. These signatures, exemplified by schemes like SPHINCS, rely on minimal assumptions and offer a straightforward path to implementation and proof of security. They also pose a lower risk during consensus debates due to their understandable nature.
Conversely, lattice-based signatures promise more advanced functionalities such as threshold signatures and key rerandomization, albeit currently at the cost of practicality in terms of size and efficiency. Despite the theoretical advantages that lattices might provide, the actual implementation and everyday usability of these schemes still require significant development. The community has expressed a need for further research into compact keys and signatures, as well as integer-only arithmetic to avoid complications from floating-point operations.
Moreover, the integration of these cryptographic methods into Bitcoin's ecosystem is subject to extensive debate. Some community members advocate for the exploration of hybrid schemes that might combine the strengths of different cryptographic approaches. However, the complexity and potentially increased size of hybrid implementations raise concerns about their practical deployment and the technical debt they could generate. Discussions also highlight the importance of ensuring that any new cryptographic scheme must not only secure against quantum attacks but also remain practical and efficient for everyday use within the blockchain framework.
In summary, while there is enthusiasm for advancing cryptographic research and potentially integrating more robust PQC methods, the Bitcoin community remains cautious. The focus is on balancing innovation with the security, efficiency, and practical constraints that define the cryptocurrency's operational environment. This ongoing dialogue underscores the community's commitment to a thoughtful and conservative approach towards adopting new technologies, ensuring that any changes align with the foundational principles and long-term viability of Bitcoin.</summary>
